1 (vi) The police chief or superintendent of a State law enforcement
2 agency;
3 (vii) The sheriff of a county;
4 (viii) An officer who is on probationary status on initial entry into a
5 law enforcement agency;
6 (ix) A correctional officer as defined in § 8–201 of the Correctional
7 Services Article; or
8 (x) Any federal law enforcement officer who exercises the powers set
9 forth in § 2–104 of the Criminal Procedure Article.
10 [(9)] (11) “Offense” means a violation of the criminal laws of the State or
11 any political subdivision of the State.
12 [(10)] (12) “Statement of charges” means a charging document, other than
13 a citation, filed in District Court by a peace officer, a District Court Judge, or a District
14 Court Commissioner.
15 (b) An application filed in the District Court that requests that a statement of
16 charges be filed against a law enforcement officer, emergency services personnel, AN
17 ADULT PROTECTIVE SERVICES WORKER, A CHILD WELFARE CASEWORKER, or an
18 educator for an offense allegedly committed in the course of executing the duties of the law
19 enforcement officer, emergency services personnel, ADULT PROTECTIVE SERVICES
20 WORKER, CHILD WELFARE CASEWORKER, or educator shall immediately be forwarded
21 to the State’s Attorney.
22 (c) (1) Upon receiving an application filed in District Court requesting that a
23 statement of charges be filed against a law enforcement officer, emergency services
24 personnel, AN ADULT PROTECTIVE SERVICES WORKER, A CHILD WELFARE
25 CASEWORKER, or an educator, the State’s Attorney shall:
26 (i) Investigate the circumstances of the matter; and
27 (ii) Make a recommendation to the District Court Commissioner as
28 to whether a statement of charges should be filed against the law enforcement officer,
29 emergency services personnel, ADULT PROTECTIVE SERVICES WORKER, CHILD
30 WELFARE CASEWORKER, or the educator.
31 (2) If the State’s Attorney recommends to a District Court Commissioner
32 that a statement of charges be filed against a law enforcement officer, emergency services
33 personnel, AN ADULT PROTECTIVE SERVICES WORKER, A CHILD WELFARE
34 CASEWORKER, or an educator, the State’s Attorney shall also make a recommendation as
35 to whether a summons or warrant should issue.

4 HOUSE BILL 302
1 (d) Notwithstanding any other provision of the Code or the Maryland Rules, a
2 statement of charges for an offense allegedly committed in the course of executing the
3 duties of the law enforcement officer, emergency services personnel, ADULT PROTECTIVE
4 SERVICES WORKER, CHILD WELFARE CASEWORKER, or the educator may not be filed
5 against a law enforcement officer, emergency services personnel, AN ADULT PROTECTIVE
6 SERVICES WORKER, A CHILD WELFARE CASEWORKER, or educator until the State’s
7 Attorney has investigated the circumstances of the matter and made recommendations to
8 the District Court Commissioner in accordance with subsection (c) of this section.
9 (e) This section may not be construed to preclude the State’s Attorney from
10 making a determination that an information should be filed against a law enforcement
11 officer, emergency services personnel, AN ADULT PROTECTIVE SERVICES WORKER, A
12 CHILD WELFARE CASEWORKER, or an educator or that a grand jury should be convened
13 to determine whether an indictment should be filed.
14 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
15 October 1, 2025.

